		<div class="postbody">
			
			<h3 >
								<a href="#p56669">Re: Pinging - How to prevent it</a>
			</h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=56669&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204#p56669"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=14322&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204">Goatboy</a></strong> on Mon Apr 25, 2011 1:09 am			<br />([msg=56669]see Re: Pinging - How to prevent it[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">I can't imagine a modern scenario in which a simple ping attack would work.  If you're playing online games, you almost certainly have enough bandwidth to deal with even a dedicated attacker on a similar line.  Besides, ping attacks are old.  Very old.  It's more than likely a problem with the game itself or the server.<br /><br />However if you want to block pings, you can probably find an option in your router to do it.  Barring that, Google how to add a rule to your firewall to block pings.</div>

			<div id="sig56669" class="signature"><div align="center"><span style="font-style: italic">Assume that everything I say is or could be a lie.</span></div><div align="center">1UHQ15HqBRZFykqx7mKHpYroxanLjJcUk</div></div>
		</div>

