			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=56719&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204#p56719"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=27413&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204">Spectre557</a></strong> on Wed Apr 27, 2011 5:11 pm			<br />([msg=56719]see Re: Pinging - How to prevent it[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">I've had a load of headaches in the past with games and network/lag problems of all sorts. I'd say your best bet would be to search for others who've had the same problem. Depending on the game, there could be any number of obscure ways to fix it if it's a known issue.<br /><br />If you get the same sort of lag when playing other games online, then you might want to try using a wired connection to your router (assuming you're using wireless) and/or other general stuff like that - this fixed a similar lag problem for me on Battlefield 2 a few years ago.</div>

			<div id="sig56719" class="signature"><span style="font-weight: bold">Current obsession:</span> <a href="http://www.minecraft.net/" class="postlink">Minecraft</a></div>
		</div>

