	<div id="p56743" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			
			<h3 >
								<a href="#p56743">Re: Pinging - How to prevent it</a>
			</h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=56743&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204#p56743"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=40455&amp;sid=e04bf280d2e70ab04ccfebe346a6a204">Dwere134</a></strong> on Thu Apr 28, 2011 5:29 pm			<br />([msg=56743]see Re: Pinging - How to prevent it[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">I'm not trying to completely oust the idea of you being targeted in an attack. But a game that old - I've never played it I can't be sure - is likely not going to have script kiddies in it who want to take enough time to dos attack you.  It's an old game, your router is old, there's probably just a glitch that causes certain events in the game to go slower or freeze up. Barring that, if it is a legitimate attack, then the previous suggestions, of blocking ping, and other known dos attacks with a rule on your firewall/router whatever it is you're using for security. And if you are able to obtain the mac address/ip address of the attacker(s) then you could probably report the issue to your ISP or local authorities as well, though it's not guaranteed to cause any kind of legal action to be taken against them. It's a video game, you aren't being incurred any monetary damages from it, nor is anybody in any physical harm, so chances are slim that reporting it will do much. Good luck though!<br />Keep us updated.</div>

			<div id="sig56743" class="signature">Dwere (David)<br /><blockquote><div><cite>Goatboy wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><cite>Dwere wrote:</cite>I'm not one to start some branch of religion though. Not my thing.</div></blockquote><br />Of course if you wanted to, you could call it the Davidians!</div></blockquote></div>
		</div>

